Each end has a fitting designed for a 1/4-inch compression joint and worked perfectly. You'll need a 1/2-inch wrench to tighten. The braided covering over the 1/4-inch tubing appears to be polyester or something similar; it doesn't restrict the movement of the tubing and is designed to protect it from abrasions and cuts. title: Does what it says it will do - saves you money!
text:
Don't want to spend $1.20+ every time you want to make a cup of coffee using your Nespresso Vertuo coffee machine? Get this Geesta refill system. Yes, the creama is a little less than the Nespresso pod produces, but not by much. And yes, it looks a bit scary at first, but it really isn't. Just take your time and it is easy. While the 1st one I did took about 2 minutes to finish by the 10th one, I was going from start to finish in under 1 minute - talk about a cost savings!

While making 15 cups doesn't make me an expert, refilling 15 pods and making 15 perfect cups does add a bit of credibility to my review. A couple of things - get a softer, smaller brush to clean the rim of grounds as the one included in the kit is a bit too big and stiff; pack the very finely grounds down using the back of the included scoop but not too hard and leave about 1 mm of gap between the rim and the coffee. Use a needle nose pliers to remove the last bit of foil from around the rim before you put the new lid on. It is a great system and I am looking forward to enjoying many, many cups of really good coffee!.

When I started wanting to make my own pods for my Keurig rather than buying the prepackaged ones (more expensive) I quickly found out why the prepackaged pods are so popular. However the coffee tended to always have grinds and a lot of residue at the bottom of the cup. Simple, buy a filter. I quickly discovered that all filters are not equal.

I've found that the key things for me are the flaps that hang over the top edge and the thickness of the filter. This filter gets A+ on both of these. The oversized flaps allow me to really fill the pod to the top and still not get grinds in my cup. They also make it super easy to clean up afterwards by grabbing the edge to pull out the soggy filter. The thickness is just right as well and allows for great flavor without any tears (especially nice when you are cleaning up.
These fit my Keurig unit perfectly. The filters remove the excess residue that was always in the bottom of my coffee cup and make cleanup virtually nothing. The only thing I do now is rinse the lid. Needless to say I love these filters!!!!!

If you have a Keurig and use the pod unit for your own coffee (rather than prepackaged Kpods, then you should buy these now. You will not regret it.

text:
We actually intended to purchase the KUDE50FXSS because it is cheaper but our 9.5 yr old Fisher Paykel died at Thanksgiving and, by Monday, I was anxious to get a replacement installed. The appliance store was out of the KUDE50FXSS because it is such a popular model, but they had a floor model of the KUDE70FXSS on sale for less than the one we wanted, so I took it. I didn't really want the very top (third) rack that one reviewer raved about and after about three uses, we removed it. The top (second rack) has two positions. In the 'down' position, it interferred with some of our dishes in the bottom rack, and in the 'up' position it interferred with the very top rack. Fortunately the very top rack is very easy to remove.

This DW has more features than we need and I don't like heated dry because it is so hot. Frankly, the final rinse water is hot enough that dishes dry on their own in the dishwasher.I have tried washing glassware along with a couple of greasy microwave bacon cookers and have tried washing some really dirty pots (in pot scrubber mode) along with glassware, and everything came out very clean both times. The filter needs to be rinsed infrequently and all the rack adjustment options make it really easy to load. Some customers may like all of the wash options and those who don't can just ignore them. For the majority of people, I suspect that the KUDE50FXSS would be just fine.

There are some plastic parts that are too delicate. We had to order replacements for several of them because numbskulls had broken them while playing with the unit at the appliance store. Also, the utensil rack has several plastic inserts with slots designed to keep your flatware separated so it won't "spoon". Our flatware doesn't fit in the slots so we removed them also. We have washed with cascade powder and Finish Powerballs. Both seem to work well and we mostly use the powerballs now. We also use JetDry in the dispenser.
.
This unit is so quiet, you actually have to listen very carefully to detect that it is on. The loudest sound is heard through the disposal when it empties. We highly recommend this unit, or the next one or two down, which most customers will likely find just as acceptable at a lower price.

title: Excellent medium-sized refrigerator.
text:
I bought my LG LTCS20020W top-freezer refrigerator from a local Lowes, so you won't see an Amazon purchase notice. Shrug. I've only owned it for a short while, but here's the skinny:

FREEZER:

The top freezer hits the ideal 0 degrees F in just a few hours by setting the thermostat on the center position. I deliberately bought a unit with no ice maker on the theory that ice makers are notorious troublemakers. DOWNSIDE: there's NO FREEZER LIGHT. I stuck a little Motion Sensor LED Night Light to the freezer roof to fix the issue.

REFRIGERATOR:

The refrigerator achieved 37-40 degrees F in a few hours with the thermostat only on the second position. My fridge is a simple unit with LED light, two crisper drawers, a smallish dairy bin and two shelves. Some units include an optional door alarm and pantry drawer, but not mine.

OVERALL:

This LG top-freezer refrigerator is VERY quiet and energy efficient. The dimensions are excellent for my small kitchen and contains enough food for over a week for my wife and I. This refrigerator is just a tiny bit shorter and narrower than some, which can be a major plus when situating it in some kitchens, especially in older houses. But the refrigerator is an inch or two deeper than some, so measure carefully.

I didn't realize it at first, but the doors are reversible. The fridge comes set up with the doors opening to the right, but even an inexperienced person (like myself) can switch the hardware so the doors open to the left in an hour by following the on-line videos.

LG refrigerators have a some of the best reputations for reliability, so I'm expecting this LG LTCS20020 to outlast me. Five stars.

title: Nice, but say "goodbye" to your drawers. Good and bad aspects.
text:
After 15 years I had to replace my Jenn-Air glass top stove when a flashlight fell from the vent hood and broke a corner. (Grump!) I didn't want an inductance stove and Consumer Reports gave the GE JP5030SJSS 30" radiant stove high marks. I bought the stove and, of course, Amazon reduced the price $110 the next day! (Double grump.)

The stove is gorgeous and I'm glad to get rid of those pesky knobs that make cleaning the sleek stove surface awkward. The touch-sensitive surface controls four burners with a quiet musical tone when activated or changing temperature. Burners heat up FAST--about ten seconds for full blast. Lights indicate hot burners even during the cool down phase. Activating the safety lock prevents accidental touches from turning on burners.

DOWNSIDES:

The true exterior dimensions of this stove are 20-7/8 X 29-3/4. This proved a minor issue since my Jenn-Air used a slightly larger cutout.

For crying out loud, GE, include a set of wire nuts and maybe a conduit connector! They cost almost nothing. I reused my old wire nuts, but come on.

BIGGEST PROBLEM: The GE JP5030SJSS places a big honkin' box at the bottom rear of the stove, plus the overall thickness measures considerably more than my Jenn-Air or a standard coil burner stove. You are either going to have to retrofit your stove drawers or remove face plates, attach them to the cabinet and kiss off your drawers. I cut off about four inches from my drawer backs and shaved off half an inch from the top edges, but many people don't have the tools or experience for this retrofit. Be warned!

Four stars.

title: I didn't need this, but . . .
text:
Lint builds up over the years in the dryer vent and can either start mucking up your drying cycle or even catch fire if it gets too hot. You should clean the duct every 2-3 years as part of your household routine.

I only have a short run of aluminum flex duct feeding to an outside wall, so it would have been just as easy to replace the duct with a new one. If you have a hard pipe that feeds up the walls, however, you really NEED this Deflector Dryer Duct Cleaning Kit or similar.

This solidly-made kit extends up to 12-feet with six soft fiberglass sections tipped with steel threads and a fat, soft brush head. You can just shove it down the duct by hand or use an electric drill to spin clean the duct with a clockwise spin. (NOTE: you MUST use clockwise--counterclockwise will unscrew the sections!) The long, soft fiberglass sections sorta flop sideways all over the place when using a drill, so you might need to slowly feed it in a section at a time. When I finished, I also used a blower to blast out the last of the lingering dust.

NOTE: Don't tear up the package it ships in--just pull out the staples. When finished you can easily repack and store the tough package on the wall.

NOTE 2: You might be able to use this kit to clean refrigerator coils. They also need to be cleaned every 2-3 years for proper operation and cooling efficiency.

This is a solid five-star cleaning kit.

title: Energy-efficient dryer with modern features.
text:
My 30-year-old Kenmore dryer (wow!) was on its last legs, so I researched on line reviews and Consumer Reports. The Samsung DV56H9100GG was well-regarded, but CR listed it as #1 which sealed the deal for me. I bought mine at Home Depot and they delivered it within the week.

I've been using my new dryer for several months and it is quite a step up over the old Kenmore. It is very quiet and energy efficient. Plus there are a variety of spiffy drying options that weren't there in the old days: a "Wrinkle Prevent" to keep clothes looking good if you can't get back to the dryer in time; "Wrinkle Away" for clean stuff that just needs a spritzing and tumble dry; a variety of settings for anything from light blouses to heavy towels and bedding, and an illuminated drum so you can see what you are doing. They even include a drying rack for tennis shoes, toys, etc., though I usually just stick stuff like that out on the back porch to dry.

The Samsung dryer is several inches taller than my old Kenmore, which makes me glad I didn't buy the pedestal that raises it off the floor; I don't think it would have fit in my available space and I certainly couldn't fold stuff on the top surface. In any case, check the dimensions of your laundry area before buying.

This Samsung dryer looks O.K. (shrug, it IS basically a big box) and appears well made. It sounds cute soft musical tones and tunes to signal different features. The "load finished" tune is rather long and resembles (to me) an 8-bit version of a "Pirates of the Caribbean" drinking song. ;) The lint trap is tucked on the door edge for easy access. Unfortunately, my new dryer door opens to the right and it appears to be a tremendous hassle--possibly impossible--to change the hinge direction.

This is a pricey critter and if I ever have a problem I'll post an update immediately. I doubt I'll get 30 years like I did with my old Kenmore, but this is a really nice clothes dryer. Five stars.

title: Nothing but trouble... but eventually fixed by Samsung
text:
We got our Samsung RF23J9011 from Home Depot in September 2018 for about $2700 give or take. Man o' man, do I wish I had read the Amazon reviews first! Who thinks about Amazon for large home appliances?

Wee bough the RF23J9011 based on its list of features, which are impressive. We were limited to a counter-depth style and wanted French Doors. We didn't want to pay for Wi-Fi, or some fancy video see-though. The RF23J9011 had exactly the features that we wanted and none that we didn't.

Pre-Covid, delivery was a snap and we had our new Samsung within a week of ordering it. We loved it for about a month.

The first thing that disappointed us was the limited capacity of the icemaker. With only 3 of us we noticed that sometimes we would run out of ice. Not terribly often, but disappointing for a new $2700 refrigerator that we would have for the next 10-15 years. And then after about 3 months, not ice at all. A quick inspection revealed that the ice maker had frozen up, as if there was a leak in it. We chipped away the ice build up manually and the ice maker started working again. We never did find a leak. Then it happened again about 5 weeks later. Exactly the same. A quick check on the internet revealed that almost all of the RF23J9011s had the same problem. A design flaw. Then we started to read about other problems.

When it was 18 months old, the freezer compartment started going wonky. I bought a thermometer to monitor the temperature. Over the course of a couple of weeks it varied from about 10 degrees F to 30 degrees, all the while being set a t (and reading) -5F. I tried unluggingi it to reset the computer. No go. Then it stopped working altogether intermittently. We looked for a local repair service to fix it, and could only find one that worked on Samsungs. They told us some very scary things about Samsung refrigerators, but came out and use an infrared temperature gun to determine that the cooling was OK, but the fan was probably bad. It took a week to get a fan and $262 later the repairman left and said wait 24 hours and call in the morning. The fan didn't fix the problem and the repair guy said he would have to replace the motherboard, but that parts from Samsung were notoriously hard to get. By this time we had long ago transferred everything from the freezer compartments to the large chest freezer in the garage, so things weren't so bad. But after waiting about 3 weeks, the refrigerator started to die.

Now I'd had enough and called Samsung. They gave us the number of the only authorized Samsung repair service called Service Quick. It took me over 2 weeks to get an appointment. When the guy finally shows up, the refrigerator had been completely dead for 10 days. We used bags of ice to keep stuff inside cool. What a mess. It only takes him 15 minutes to tell me that this was a "sealed system problem", meaning everything was still under warranty, and that he's pick up a compressor and be back --- in about 2 weeks. When there was no return call from Service Quick 3 weeks later, I wrote a very long and nasty letter to the Corporate Offices. Two days later I got an email and a phone call from one of the Vice-Presidents, telling me how sorry he was, and promising to call Service Quick and get them out to the house ASAP. A week later I called Service Quick to find out what was happening and they asked me if I wanted schedule a service call. I nearly had a stroke. After scheduling a service call (for about 15 days later), I emailed the Samsung VP back and also tried to call the direct number that he'd given me in the first email. I left a message.

Then I ordered a tiny refrigerator from Amazon I(RCA RFR320-B-Black-COM RFR321 Mini Refrigerator, 3.2 Cu Ft,
$144.99 that arrived in 2 days. I called the VP back he was very apologetic and promised me a full refund. That was a week ago and I've heard nothing back since.

The Service Quick guy is scheduled to come back in 5 days so we'll see. If he can't fix it, I'l order something else. Why haven't I done that already? Same reason that the Samsung VP didn't offer me a new refrigerator. Almost everything seems to have a 3-6 week wait because of Covid.

So Samsung refrigerators suck and it is virtually impossible to get them repaired.

DO NOT BUY A SAMSUNG REFRIGERATOR

JM Tepper

ps. a year and a half later. Not too long after I wrote the original one star review, the refrigerator section completely quit. I had had enough. I called Samsung Corporate offices directly and got the email address of the President. I emailed him the whole story up to that point, demanding a new refrigerator. Within 24 hours I got a reply from some senior VP who promised to send a Samsung team out to me and guaranteed that if they couldn't fix all the problems with the refrigerator, that they would indeed replace it with a new unit.

The Samsung crew arrived a few days later right on schedule and after about 30 minutes, diagnosed the problem as a "sealed system" problem meaning that the guts of the cooling system had a leak or blockage. They were able to isolate the block, drained the whole system, cleared the blockage, checked the tubes for leaks and refilled it. Problem solved. They also replaced the entire Icemaker. All under warrantee, didn't cost me a dime (except for all the food that went bad earlier).

Now, about 1.5 years later, the refrigerator has been working like a charm every since Samsung was here. The moral of the story is that if you have a problem with a Samsung refrigerator, don't call Sears, don't call a local repair shop, go directly to Samsung.

On the basis of this, I changed the original 1 star rating to 3 stars.

title: 80% seal failure on refilled pods
text:
Note the photos: the one showing two Vertuo pods has the factory fill on the left and the refilled pod on the right, the photo with four pods shows a random sample of refilled pods all showing some level of seal failure.
The refilled pods all made Pretty Good coffee, about like our old Keurig on a good day, although the crema is largely absent on account of the poor seal (the Vertuo operates at much higher pressure then the Keurig, so if the seal on the pod is flawed you don't get high pressure extraction, hence no crema). And, it's all about the crema, right campers?
The positives: we could source organic coffee for refilling the pods
The negative: no crema to speak of, laborious emptying, cleaning/washing/drying of the pods, and then the refilling which is labor intensive to the point where I wonder why I'm not just using a burr grinder and espresso machine…
I really like the Vertuo; anyone can make a durn good cuppa with these things. The availability of third party pods is, however, nonexistent and that is troubling as Nestle has never been on the cutting edge of organic Fair-Trade in sourcing their coffee products.
In the meantime, after having used the Geesta system for six months and over 300 pods, I am reluctantly going back to the Nestle product.
Three stars is really generous of me but the product intent is good and maybe you will have better luck achieving an effective and consistent pod seal.

title: Thumbs In The Middle
text:
This range hood is definitely a decent one for the price, but has some shortcomings that I would rather do without. The first problem is the noise. The fan is VERY loud due to the rather thin sheet metal that is used in it's construction. It ends up amplifying the sound rather than dampening it.

I am also not a big fan (no pun intended) of buttons on stoves due to the fact that they inevitably get gunked up with grease and are almost impossible to clean. There are quite a few models out there that use touch screens, which is what I would prefer. Other than that, the item works exactly as it should. Installation was simple. Te instructions were not great, but I figured it out on my own.

title: Solid Performance With Sleek Design
text:
This range hood is exactly what I needed for my new, gas stove. The house did not have an existing fan or vent and this one was just the right size and capacity. The best feature of this system is the touch keys. I have used other ones that had knobs or buttons and they always ending up collecting grease and gunk that are very difficult to clean. With this one there re no nooks or crannies for anything to get into, so cleaning is super quick and simple.

The two fans provide more than enough airflow for my stove. If anything, I would say that the two fans are overkill and make a bit more noise than I would like. The overhead light is more than bright enough. Unfortunately, it does give off a pretty harsh, full spectrum light that you wouldn't want to have to use for long periods, but is good enough for cooking.

Construction is of pretty solid sheet metal and there are no imperfections of any kind. Installation is simple if you know what you are doing. I hard wired mine to a 15 AMP circuit, which is more than enough to power it as well as the electric controls of my gas stove. An excellent product.

title: A Bit Much
text:
As many other reviewers have pointed out, this is a rather ginormous appliance that takes up quite a bit of space. For that reason alone, it probably isn't the best choice for most people. It weighs a ton when it is filled with water and isn't easy to cart around when it's empty, either.

I would say that this unit would probably be appropriate in very large, open areas like a garage or perhaps a very large living room. It is really overkill for someplace like a bedroom though. Assuming that you have such a large area, the product works fairly well. The large amount of water it holds means that you will not need to refill it for several hours at a time, which can be a problem with the smaller devices.

Due to potential mold build-up you will need to rinse this unit out occasionally, which is a bit of a chore. Just picking it up and lugging it around is quite a chore. There are no handles or other easy way to grasp the device. I would recommend only using distilled water in this device in order to minimize how often you will need to clean it.

I certainly can't complain that the product does not work as intended. It is just a bit more than most people need and not worth the extra upkeep to me.

title: Lightweight Electric Stovetop
text:
This is a fairly lightweight and portable electric cooking stove that plugs into any ordinary household outlet. It's lightweight construction has positives and negatives. It is light and easy to move around for when you aren't using it, but it also does not support very large pots/pans. So, if you think that you are going to be able to put a tea kettle on one burner and a full-sized skillet on the other burner you can forget about it. The heating elements are way too close together for large pots or pans, so you can only use one that is full-sized at a time.

The heating elements themselves are fairly small, so if you are trying to heat a large skillet it will only get to full temperature towards the center. For those of you who don't know the difference between a full-sized electric stove and one of these portable units you should keep in mind that most electric ovens with burners are directly connected to a dedicated 220V circuit, which gives them FAR more energy than a standard 110V power outlet. The result is that neither of the burners gets anywhere near as hot as the heating coils on an electric oven. Water takes longer to boil. Food takes longer to cook. So, be sure to allow for more cooking time than you normally would with an electric oven.

Despite its limitations, for its current price of around $23 this portable electric stove is a bargain. It's something that can easily be dragged into the back yard for BBQs or for plugging in anywhere outdoors. It is not perfect for every situation, but for some situations it works perfectly.

title: Good product with a couple of drawbacks
text:
I went online to purchase paper filters for my Chemex, and then saw this product and decided to give it a whirl. Below are pros and cons:

Pros:
- Filter works very well. I used on two successive mornings and coffee was delicious.
- Good quality. Fits perfectly into the Chemex. Also, I appreciated the rubber gasket that goes along the top of the cone; this creates a good seal so if you happen to pour too much water into the filter, the grounds won't seep into the Chemex.

Cons:
- Usability. I didn't like the procedure. Think of it this way: You pour the very hot water through the filter; after all the water is poured you're ready to pour a cup of coffee, so you remove the filter. It doesn't drip much because the filter holes are very fine, however there are still wet grounds in there. So you turn it over to dump them out (I put them into a plastic receptacle and then do a weekly dump into the compost pile), but the metal part of the cone where you have to hold it is very hot (obviously because you just poured 210 degree water through there). You manage this, but still about 20% of the grounds are sticking onto the filter, which requires you to manually wipe them out with a paper towel or something. And the cone is still hot. After wiping them out there's still about 5% of the grounds in there, mostly stuck in the very bottom of the cone. So your last recourse is to rinse it into the sink. This allows grounds to go into the drain; I wipe as much as I can out of the sink, but inevitably some slip into the drain, and coffee grounds and drains are not a good match. As long as you're in the sink, you may as well wash the filter with soap, etc. Meanwhile, back at the Chemex, some heat loss has occurred with the coffee. This was my experience anyway. Maybe there is a better "workflow" for this, but I just found it infinitely easier to remove and discard the paper filter with grounds.

- Cleaning and longevity. Some reviews I read mentioned that they had issues with the filter clogging. Indeed, in the packaging there are actually instructions on how to clean, and what to do if it clogs. Putting in dishwasher, soaking in vinegar, etc. Nothing that's a big deal. But the fact that they addressed this in the packaging gives credibility to the reviews that cite this as an issue. And so the question then becomes, do you want to spend time maintaining a filter.

Neutral:
- Price is still probably a little steep, but it should pay for itself after a year (or less depending on how much you brew) of use.

Conclusion:
I'm rating this 4 stars because I don't think there's anything wrong with the product. It does what it says it will do, and it seems to do it well, which is to serve as a substitute for paper filters. However I decided to return due to the "usability" issue described above. My mornings are already a multitasking bonanza with making breakfast, packing lunches, feeding the dog, etc and I just don't need to add anything else to the morning workflow. If this doesn't describe you though then it might be a good fit.

I was surprised to see how non-waterproof this is however. Water running down a roof and hitting the top edge will just flow right into the enclosure. But this is by design, water can just flow right across the base plate inside the enclosure and out the bottom. The 10" opening for the air duct has a large upward lip on it, so water can't get in there. But Broan was careless with the 1/2 hole for the electrical connection, water can get in here. I bought a water-tight romex clamp which has a gasket for panel mounting, that took care of that, and I also used a high quality sealant across the top and down both sides. I left the bottom open so water can escape, if any were to get in their now.

I had a roofer install the unit. He did not like the very short mounting edges, hardely 2 inches of the baseplate on all sides. I had to find a metal shop that added a wide baseplate and used lots of sealant and rivets to attach. This Broan unit is aluminum, which takes special equipment to weld, so rivets is probably the only choice.

I installed a Broan 72W variable speed control in my kitchen, which works as advertised, though there is an audible 60 cycle hum from the motor that I'll bet originates with this controller. When running the fan in a medium to low speed range this hum is irritating imho, after all these large blowers and controls are Broan's premier products in kitchen ventilation. But that's more an attribute of the control. This blower would be 5 stars except for all the additional work needed when installing. I'm expecting many years of trouble free use.

title: Too short, difficult to set up, but otherwise okay.
text:
Pros:
1. Uses a standard Edison plug (i.e. parallel blade with a ground). This can be either a pro or a con. For me it was problematic because the outlet for my washer and dryer was on only a 20 amp circuit. A 30-amp dryer plug would have been more convenient for me. That said, it is nice to know that I can use this dryer if my next apartment doesn't have a dryer outlet.
2. Decent little workhorse--takes some time to get things dry, but it does what it's designed to do.
3. Lightweight--I don't feel like I'll be over-burdening my friends if I ever ask them to help me move.
Cons:
1. It's far too short -- plan on either mounting it to the wall, building a pedestal, or developing back problems. If I were to recommend a redesign for the next model it would be to put the controls near the top.
2. The vent on the back is a non-standard size (about 3 3/8 inches). This made putting a dryer tube on the back a pain. I followed the advice of another reviewer and removed some of the wire from a 4" wide flexible aluminum duct and was able to clamp it on with some careful finagling.
3. Drum wouldn't spin on first running the machine. I had to open it up and wrap the belt around the drum to get it to spin (I don't really knock stars off for this, since it happens from time to time; but I mention it for anyone who does buy it--if it doesn't spin at first, unplug it, take of the back panel and have a look before returning it -- saved me a shipping headache).

Overall:
If your choice is no dryer or this dryer, buy this dryer. I really like having a dryer, but I don't particularly like having this dryer. Between it's height and the difficulty attaching the hose to the vent, I don't think I'd buy it again. That said, it is a decent bargain, and it does the job I need it to do. I can't hate it too much.

Its in a small closet so we looked- no screws fallen out anywhere nearby.... we replaced the heater element and it worked fine for a little while... but I should not have let Sears off so easily about the missing screws... in the 8 months since then I have had to replace both pumps, two heat sensors, the dryer fan, and the faceplate is showing cracks from underneath where it connects to the main washer body that have likely been slowly propagating since day 1. I am 100% sure this unit was not put together correctly at the factory and basically had been shaking itself to peices that first year unbenknownst to me and now that the warranty expired before I found any of the problems I am left with a two grand priced lemon of a washer dryer and doubtful it will last another year even with replacing almost every part imaginable.... Next time, I will get one straight from LG or ANYONE else as long as they have an all in one washer and ventless dryer thats about 4.5 cu ft, or I am going to just get a decent front loader and go back to old school hang drying... but never another Kenmore appliance after this fiasco.

title: Best Out There
text:
The best thing about these filters is you can fill them with loose leave tea, shake them on the counter, and NOT see a bunch of fine tea particles and dust on your counter (like you can with most any other product). That also means they don't release these particles into the tea water itself, and as a result you don't have to use a strainer.

The mesh on these is like the goldtone filter used for coffee makers since the 1980s or so. They keep particles out of the water.

What I'd like to see to make these better is hinged "wings" that flip up so the filters can be used over wider tea pots.

As it is, I need to buy both sizes depending on the opening of my various tea pots. If they had "wings" that flipped up until they were horizontal I wouldn't have to do that.

At any rate, they work great and it's great to not have to use a strainer when pouring tea.

These are currently the only tea strainers Grace Teas and Mark T. Wendell (where Julia Child bought her tea) offer for sale, and I'm sured they've tried just about every design out there before settling on these.

These are also much easier to clean up after using because the mesh is so fine particles don't get stuck in the mesh the way they do with tea balls.

The product could be improved with wings so it can be used in even wider opening tea pots,, and there's no need to use the lid when using in a tea pot (use the pot's lid instead), but other than that, there's nothing that performs better at keeping dust and fine particles off your counters and out of your water. Highly recommended.

title: Poorly Thought Out Dish Rack, Otherwise Quite Good
text:
Whoever designed the dish rack that rolls in and out of the unit doesn't have a clue about what its function is. Average sized dishes are too tall to stand straight up so need to be positioned at an angle, and there's no easy way to do that.

Tip:

As soon as you run into the problem bend every single metal prong forward about 10 degrees on each side and you can suddenly fit all your normal-sized dishes in the dishwasher at a slight angle forever after and they'll still clean just as well. They should have designed it this way.

Worse, the bottom of the rack has a "hole" toward the back that (I guess) is where the utensils basket is supposed to go because nothing else can without falling through to the bottom. This is beyond stupid, as you may need to move the basket forward to fit something. This situation is made worse in that the holes in the bottom of the basket are too small to allow any of the upward projections from the dish rack fit through the bottom so you can place it pretty much anywhere else you want, AND if you put the basket over that hole it will tilt at times and obstruct the washer arm.

Rocket scientists, whoever designed the dish holder rack and basket, are not.

So while loading it can be a needless hassle, as the bars in the basket are just too far apart in many places and this also affects where you can stack things like bowls or cups or small saucers, otherwise it works pretty well, and I find for economy the P3 setting (which the manual says is about 70 minutes -- the shortest one possible) washes well without running on and on for a very long time, and the dishes come out clean anyway, so why would you want to run it longer?

I'm still a little confused as to why the cycle stops for long periods of time and the display flashes (indicating the wash cycle isn't yet complete) and it seems to be doing nothing, and yet it's not done because it's not yet drained the water (and the display stops flashing). Maybe it's heating the dishes to sterilize them or something? I don't know, but at any rate just leave it alone and wait until the display stops flashing and the unit beeps multiple times in succession. That's when it's done, and that's when you'll want to turn off the faucet, press the red button at the faucet attachment to release the water pressure, and then turn off the dishwasher's power button, open the door, and pull the basket forward to let the dishes air dry (or "spot dry" them with a towel (there's so much heat inside the dishwasher at this point they'll be mostly dry anyway).

Keep in mind placement can be a problem since it's a big unit and needs to be within about 6" of your countertop height for the water to drain correctly. Some people may need to get a cart at this height and roll it near the sink. We got a restaurant supply stainless cart from online (but honestly, if you're going to go to that expense you may as well just move up to a $500+ GE or similar dishwasher that would be taller, that you could fit twice the dishes in (without the hassles), its own cart (rolls), and it would give you some work surface on top).

Other than these quibbles, and the owner's manual being so poorly written and in a tiny almost illegible typeface and print quality, it's been a good buy, especially since I was able to find an open box unit online for $175 that I called about and ultimately got for $150 including free shipping.

At that price I wasn't expecting much, but it's been a pleasant surprise, with just the reservations I mentioned, which could easily be fixed the next time the company updates the product in any way.

_________________________________

UPDATE:

Nine months later and it still works as good as new, but if I had it to do over again I would buy a full-sized dishwasher on wheels since this one sometimes has to be run twice to do the stuff used to make a dinner with a main course and one or two side dishes, and each time I run it it's 70 minutes where I'm stuck waiting for it since I don't want to leave the house with the pressure still on on the water at the faucet (which it will be until you close the taps and press the red button to release it). Our apartment faucet has had to be replaced because of this pressure since the rubber seal finally gave out under the stress and it started to leak, but I think it was a shoddy faucet/installation anyway and this may not be common.

UPDATE 2:

It's now over two years later and this is still working, problem free, even though I've used it daily. Whoever designed the basket, by now it seems absolutely RIDICULOUS, but I've learned by now what will go where without falling through the too big spaces.

title: Get a better quality reusable or stick with paper filters
text:
I purchased this so I could be a little more eco friendly. I usually use 1.5-2 tablespoons of coffee each morning to make my cup.

What I've found is that this filter lets the water run through it very quickly, where as the paper lets it drip slowly. Because of this, the coffee comes out quite weak and watery. I've included a picture of what it looked like after making today's coffee. I think it will be less of a problem if you are using MORE coffee grounds for a stronger pot and/or more cups of coffee. However for the ounces of coffee I use, it's not effective.

I decided to just let the machine continue making ice and see what happened. The ice holder inside held all of the cubes and got colder as more ice was added, and the cubes did not melt like the first cubes made. So, the key is to leave the machine alone and let it make its ice and it works great! Some people complained of noise, I did not mind the fan running nor the sound of the ice dumping. Not a big deal to me. Some questions listed were afraid of mildew in the machine. I just dried it out, left the top open to air dry and don't see an issue with moisture. The cube sizes are great and are made very quickly, just like the company said. Would highly recommend!

title: Happy with my purchase (from someone who almost always suffers from buyers remorse)
text:
After doing some research, I picked this as my first wine fridge. I needed a fridge that would last me through at least 1 move and 4 more years of school, and most reviews I found on different sites from people who bought the same model fridge said they'd been running without a problem for years.
The fridge was well packaged, delivered by UPS with labels and packaging very clearly showing what was inside. No dents on the box. Easy to unpackage, and is very aesthetically appealing straight out of the box. The tint on the glass door is perfect- the interior is still visible-ish without the interior light on, so the fridge blends in perfectly with all my black shelving.
Because I went with a thermoelectric fridge over a compressor, I decided against putting it in my (poorly-ventilated) kitchen, but besides the tiny read out for temp and the buttons, it's a fairly non-descript (and small, much smaller than I imagined) addition to my living room. And its very quiet. The noise it makes is a low hum, so once I got used to the new hum in my living room, it very easy to tune out. My humidifier makes more noise than the fridge (another score for thermoelectric!).
My one gripe is that the racks inside aren't very accomodating for irregularly sized wine bottles. Of the 14 bottles I had to store, 4 couldn't fit in the standard shelving. I took one shelf out, but the rounded divets in the metal for bottles were too small for 1 bottle as well. I ended up putting 3 large bottles on the bottom shelf and stacking the 4th on top of that. It's only a gripe because it wasn't what I had planned, but I didn't deduct any stars because once the door is closed, the tinted glass doesn't show the stacked bottles. Just got it today, but will try to remember to update my review in 1 years time.

Edit:
2yrs and 2 moves in and its still going strong. I have a dedicated thermometer/hygrometer in there to make sure the temp in the door is accurate, and it is. Very, very happy with my purchase.
Of course, getting a wine fridge may mean getting more wines that you think you'll drink soon but you end up cellaring. But in this hypothetical situation, you may not have a place to cellar wines. So you may start looking for a "cellar fridge" so that the Whynter fridge can be for wines you plan on drinking soon.
